  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phil-mind-expert",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "YES — Translator's Afterword, ideal for post-experience analysis",
    "content": "**YES** — A Translator's Afterword is the ideal home for exactly the material that would have been spoilers in a Foreword or Preface. After the reader has completed the experiential sequences, a Translator's Afterword can do what we currently cannot: spell out the cross-traditional connections (Husserl's noematic structure, HOT theories of consciousness, Varela's neurophenomenology, the Buddhist Abhidharma parallels, Wittgenstein's beetle-in-a-box), discuss the significance of the natural transformation model of understanding, and articulate the other-minds argument embedded in Essay 4 — all without undermining the reader's firsthand experience. This is where the expert reports we wrote become genuinely useful to the reader: the philosophical depth we identified can be surfaced after the reader has their own experience to anchor it against. A Translator's Afterword (rather than a critical afterword by an external scholar) keeps the apparatus unified under the translation team's voice and avoids the problem of finding the right external scholar."
  }
}
